Effect of recent divergence - dispersal

Larval type – Planktotrophic/pelagic larvae leads to less CS/NS)?

Note1: for this I’m working with a separate surveylarv input file where I have corrected larval types to pt, lt, dd, and removed all others, including cases where there are multiple types checked. (Most of those cases are where the two CS have different larvae.) This left 574 CS with larval info.

Note2: the data fail the homoscedasticity test (Bartlett’s) so I’ve used a nonparametric Kruskal-Wallis test to see if CS/NS is different among groups.

##       DD       LT       PT 
## 3.552632 3.372881 3.154605
##       DD       LT       PT 
## 2.421727 3.079562 3.106330
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  as.numeric(larv_NbCS$Nb_CS) and larv_NbCS$Larv_type
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 7.9247, df = 2, p-value = 0.01902

Result: larvae with direct development have the highest number of CS/NS, and this is significant, but the graph doesn’t make this obvious (lots of noise). Hypothesis supported.

High HKK leads to more CS ss – testing this based on Nb_CS per HKK.

Note: data again failed homoscedasticity, using Kruskal Wallis test

##        1        5       10       25      100     1000 
## 3.888889 3.285714 3.480159 2.977679 3.081395 3.446970
##        1        5       10       25      100     1000 
## 2.891559 2.067359 3.072109 2.334080 1.660724 3.744338
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  HKK_NbCS$Nb_CS and HKK_NbCS$HKKv3
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 4.9941, df = 5, p-value = 0.4166

Result: No difference in the number of CS per NS across HKK classes; the average for all is around 3. Hypothesis not supported.

In sum, support for the role of recent divergence as measured by a proxy of dispersal is equivocal and depends on the proxy used.

Stabilizing selection

More stable environments = more CSss or statistical differences

Note: stable = pelagic, deepsea, cave, coralreef; not stable = coastal, intertidal, estuarine, seagrass

##        
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE   103   49
##   TRUE    190  135
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  stable_hab$CSss and stable_hab$Stable
## X-squared = 3.3992, df = 1, p-value = 0.06523
##                FALSE      TRUE
## CSss_total 0.6484642 0.7336957
## CSsl_total 0.3515358 0.2663043

Result: marginal - but in predicted direction. More CSss found in stable environments. Hypothesis supported.

Note also that stabilizing selection predicts more CSss than CSsl, which is what we find (see above).

In sum, we generally have support for this idea.

High Ne (neutral hypotheses)

Reproductive investment - Low reproductive investment leads to more statistical divergence? (Repro. investment proxy for Ne)

Note1: Again this uses the surveylarv dataset with hand cleaning. Note2: Planktotrophic = LOW; Lecithotrophic, Brooding, DD = HIGH; If a spp could be both low and high, have marked it NA (is usually bc the CS have different larval types). Anything else got marked NA to be conservative. Note3: Only 294 cases are considered here, meaning that is where we have morphological data AND larval type data

Importance of biological traits

## nod_total  0.3916667 0.2674772

Note: We do not get the same result if I just consider ss vs sl - there is no longer significance. I think this is because hard skeleton should be important for both statistical and diagnostic differences. Result: hypothesis supported.

More diagnostic traits with internal fertilization?

##                     
##                       B  E  I
##   Diagnostic         50 53 42
##   No differentiation 47 65 23
##   Statistic          37 86 46
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  surveymorpho$Morpho_diff and surveymorpho$ferti
## X-squared = 14.293, df = 4, p-value = 0.006416
##                    B         E         I
## stat_total 0.2761194 0.4215686 0.4144144
## diag_total 0.3731343 0.2598039 0.3783784
## nod_total  0.3507463 0.3186275 0.2072072

Result: hypothesis supported. Species with internal fert are more likely to have diag diffs, ie CSsl. This is also true if I remove the “both” category. Hypothesis accepted.

More diagnostic traits with external genitalia?

##                     
##                        B   N   Y
##   Diagnostic          30  75  40

##   Statistic           16 111  42

## data:  surveymorpho$Morpho_diff and surveymorpho$genitals
## X-squared = 17.304, df = 4, p-value = 0.001687
##                    B         N         Y
## stat_total 0.2105263 0.4095941 0.4117647
## diag_total 0.3947368 0.2767528 0.3921569
## nod_total  0.3947368 0.3136531 0.1960784

Result: more diagnostic traits with external, hypothesis accepted. This is also true if only considering CSss and CSsl, AND when gastropods are removed (the only class with “both”).

In sum, except “image vision” we still see an importance of taxonomic characters in determining the TYPE of CS that is found (ss vs sl).

So, overall conclusions: When looking at the full dataset, there is support for several (but not all) sets of hypotheses. Interestingly, the effect of taxonomic work/effort seems to go away, while the effect of taxonomic class remains. Some support for both selection-based and neutral ideas.
